        introduction: "Peille is one of the most secret and best-preserved villages in the Nice hinterland. Perched at 630 m altitude on a rocky spur overlooking the Paillon valley and the coastline, this medieval village offers a 360-degree panorama embracing the Mediterranean Sea, Mont Agel (1,148 m), the pre-Alps and on clear days the Corsican coast. Inhabited since Roman times, Peille was a stronghold of the County of Provence and then the County of Nice during the Middle Ages. Its vaulted lanes, covered passages, stone houses with carved lintels and tiny squares form a labyrinth of charm preserved from mass tourism. The Church of Sainte-Marie-de-l'Assomption (12th-13th century) holds an altarpiece attributed to Jean Canavesio and a painting from the Nice school. The village has kept its living traditions: every September, the Ratapignata festival (the bat, the village's emblem) celebrates local legends with a medieval procession. Peille is also the starting point for beautiful hikes towards Mont Baudon, the Col de la Madone de Peille and the ridges overlooking Monaco.",
