      en: {
        metaTitle: "Taxi Nice → Saint-Jean-Cap-Ferrat | 10 km, €25 | TaxiNeo",
        metaDescription: "Via Basse Corniche then D25, 20 min ride. Villa Ephrussi de Rothschild, Sentier du littoral and Presqu'île de luxe along the way. No toll on this route.",
        heroTitle: "Taxi Nice — Saint-Jean-Cap-Ferrat",
        heroSubtitle: "The most exclusive peninsula on the Côte d'Azur",
        description: "Taxi transfer from Nice to Saint-Jean-Cap-Ferrat, a luxury peninsula home to the Villa Ephrussi de Rothschild and paradise coastal paths.",
        routeDescription: "10 km — approximately 20 minutes via the Lower Corniche and D25",
        introduction: "Saint-Jean-Cap-Ferrat is one of the most prestigious and exclusive peninsulas in the Mediterranean. This small paradise of greenery, planted with pines and palms, is home to some of the most expensive properties in the world, where royals, billionaires and celebrities own sumptuous villas behind high stone walls. The cultural jewel of Cap Ferrat is undoubtedly the Villa Ephrussi de Rothschild, a pink Italian Renaissance-style palace surrounded by nine themed gardens with sea views on both sides of the peninsula. The coastal path circles the entire Cap in about 3 hours, offering exceptional panoramas of crystal-clear coves, the Villefranche-sur-Mer harbour and the Bay of Beaulieu. The marina at Saint-Jean hosts prestigious yachts, and the village retains a peaceful, authentic atmosphere with its seafood restaurants along the waterfront. Somerset Maugham, Charlie Chaplin and King Leopold II of Belgium are among the illustrious residents who have made their home on this enchanting peninsula.",
        itineraire: "From Nice, take the Lower Corniche (M6098) towards Monaco. The road follows Nice port then the Cap de Nice headland with views of the Villefranche harbour. After Villefranche-sur-Mer, at the Port de la Darse roundabout, turn right onto the D25 which enters the Cap Ferrat peninsula. The road first passes through the village of Saint-Jean-Cap-Ferrat, then continues to the lighthouse at the tip of the Cap. For the Villa Ephrussi de Rothschild, follow signs from Boulevard Denis Semeria. The journey is entirely toll-free on well-maintained departmental roads. Alternatively, you can take the Middle Corniche (D6007) and descend to the peninsula via Beaulieu-sur-Mer, but this detour adds 5 minutes with no particular advantage. The driver drops you at the Villa Ephrussi entrance, Saint-Jean port or your hotel on the peninsula.",
        conseils: "The Villa Ephrussi de Rothschild is open year-round but the gardens are most beautiful in spring (April-May). Allow 2 hours for a full visit (villa + 9 gardens). The coastal path is free and accessible all year: allow about 3 hours for the full circuit around the Cap. Wear enclosed shoes as some sections are rocky. In summer, the Cap's coves (Passable beach on the Villefranche side, Paloma beach on the Beaulieu side) are paradise but get crowded: arrive before 10am. Parking is very limited on the peninsula, especially in high season: a taxi eliminates this problem. For lunch, the restaurant at Saint-Jean port serves excellent fish cuisine overlooking the yachts. Easily combine with Villefranche-sur-Mer or Beaulieu-sur-Mer in the same half-day.",
        comparaisonTransport: "Bus 81 (Ligne d'Azur) connects Nice to Saint-Jean-Cap-Ferrat in 30 minutes for €1.50, with reasonable daytime frequency. There is no railway station on the peninsula (the nearest is Beaulieu-sur-Mer, 2 km away). By taxi, the 10 km journey takes only 20 minutes and you are dropped exactly at your destination — Villa Ephrussi, beach, path or hotel — a considerable advantage on this fairly spread-out peninsula.",
        faq: [
          { question: "What is the price of a taxi from Nice to Saint-Jean-Cap-Ferrat?", answer: "The fare is €25 to €35 depending on the time. The journey is short (10 km) and toll-free. Fixed price at booking." },
          { question: "How long does the journey take?", answer: "About 20 minutes via the Lower Corniche and D25. The journey is quick except in summer at peak times on the Lower Corniche (allow 30 to 35 minutes)." },
          { question: "Can the taxi drop me at the Villa Ephrussi de Rothschild?", answer: "Yes, the driver drops you directly at the entrance of Villa Ephrussi. The visitor car park is right next to the entrance." },
          { question: "Can I tour the Cap by taxi?", answer: "The coastal path is pedestrian-only, but the driver can drop you at one starting point and collect you at another after your walk. Arrange this when booking." },
          { question: "Is Saint-Jean-Cap-Ferrat suitable for children?", answer: "Yes, Paloma and Passable beaches are ideal for families. Villa Ephrussi offers activity booklets for children. The coastal path is accessible for children who walk well." },
        ],
      },
