        introduction: "Tourrettes-sur-Loup is one of the most captivating villages in the Nice hinterland, a fortified medieval town perched on a rocky promontory above the spectacular Loup Gorges. Nicknamed the 'City of Violets' as it is the last stronghold of open-field violet cultivation on the Côte d'Azur, Tourrettes celebrates the Violet Festival each March, a tradition dating back to the 19th century. The terraced violet fields on the village slopes offer an enchanting sight and fragrance from November to March. Beyond violets, Tourrettes-sur-Loup has become a centre for art craftsmanship: potters, weavers, sculptors, painters and jewellers have set up workshops in the medieval houses, creating a unique artistic trail through the stone lanes. The village itself is an architectural curiosity: the outer houses, built directly on the rock, form a continuous wall — there are no separate ramparts as the dwellings themselves serve as fortification. The Church of Saint-Grégoire houses an altarpiece from the Nice School and a 15th-century triptych attributed to the workshop of Louis Bréa. The Loup Gorges, accessible from the village, offer a vertiginous walk between waterfalls and limestone cliffs. The journey from Nice first crosses the Var plain before climbing towards Vence and the hinterland hills.",
        itineraire: "From Nice, take the Promenade des Anglais then the Cagnes road (D6007/D2210) towards Vence. Pass through Cagnes-sur-Mer, Saint-Paul-de-Vence, then Vence. From Vence, continue on the D2210 for 6 km to Tourrettes-sur-Loup. The main car park is at the village entrance, near the Grand-Place. The alternative via the A8 motorway (exit 48 Cagnes-sur-Mer) then the D36 to Vence is faster when coastal traffic is heavy. The entire journey is toll-free if you stay on departmental roads. The village is compact and entirely walkable — the taxi drops you at the central car park from where everything is within a few minutes' walk.",
        conseils: "The Violet Festival (first or second weekend of March) is the unmissable event: flower-decorated floats, flower battle, violet confectionery — book your taxi early as the village is besieged. Out of season, the artisan workshops are open year-round and it is a pleasure to visit without the crowds. Don't miss the Florian confectionery at the Pont du Loup, below the village, where you can watch artisan sweet, jam and chocolate making — free visit with tasting. The Loup Gorges are accessible via the D6 from the Pont du Loup: the Courmes Waterfall and Saut du Loup are spectacular stops. For lunch, the restaurant Clovis on the Grand-Place offers Provençal cuisine with panoramic views over the Loup valley. The path circling the outside of the village (30 minutes) offers vertiginous views over the gorges below.",
        comparaisonTransport: "Bus 400 (Ligne d'Azur) connects Nice to Vence in 1 hour for €1.50, then you need bus 511 from Vence to Tourrettes (15 min, €1.50), totalling about 1h30 with the connection. By taxi, the direct 35-minute journey drops you in the heart of the village, with no connections or waiting. A taxi is particularly recommended if you wish to combine Tourrettes with Vence or Saint-Paul-de-Vence on the same excursion.",
