        heroTitle: "Taxi Nice — Aspremont",
        heroSubtitle: "The hinterland belvedere with views from sea to Alps",
        description: "Taxi transfer from Nice to Aspremont, a perched village offering an exceptional 360° panorama from the Mediterranean Sea to the snow-capped Mercantour peaks.",
        routeDescription: "12 km — approximately 20 minutes via the D14 (Saint-Pancrace road)",
        introduction: "Aspremont is one of the closest perched villages to Nice yet one of the least known to tourists, making it a preserved gem of the Nice hinterland. Perched at 520 metres altitude on a rocky spur overlooking the Var valley, this medieval village offers an absolutely exceptional 360° panorama: on one side the Baie des Anges and the glittering Mediterranean, on the other the snow-capped peaks of the Mercantour and Mont Cima. The village has preserved its intact medieval structure with narrow lanes paved with calade (Var river pebbles), vaulted passages, tall houses pressed together for protection against the mistral, and the remains of its ancient ramparts. The parish Church of Saint-Jacques, a jewel of Niçois baroque, houses a remarkable Rosary altarpiece attributed to the school of Louis Bréa and fine 17th-century frescoes. The Chapel of the White Penitents, on the village square, completes this religious ensemble. Aspremont is the starting point for the Mont Cima trail (1,089 m), a 3-hour return hike rewarded by a panoramic view over the entire French Riviera, from the Estérel to Italy. The village cultivates a peaceful and authentic way of life, with shaded squares where time seems suspended, old wash houses and a restored communal bread oven. The journey from Nice is short but spectacular, the road climbing rapidly above the city to offer ever-expanding views.",
        itineraire: "From Nice, take the direction of Saint-Pancrace via the D14. The road immediately climbs through the residential districts of Cimiez and Saint-Pancrace, offering increasingly open views over the Bay of Nice. After Saint-Pancrace, the D14 continues in switchbacks through olive groves and pine forests to Aspremont. The village appears clinging to its rocky spur well before you arrive. The main car park is at the village entrance, from where the medieval centre is a 2-minute walk. The entire journey is toll-free and the road, though winding, is in good condition and well secured. An alternative route via Castagniers and the D114 exists but is longer without being faster.",
        conseils: "The village square, with its panorama over the Baie des Anges, is the perfect spot for a morning coffee or sunset aperitif — the light is magical in the late afternoon. The Church of Saint-Jacques deserves a visit for its altarpiece attributed to the Bréa school: ask for the key at the village café if it is closed. For walkers, the Mont Cima trail (3h return, 570 m elevation gain) is one of the finest short hikes near Nice, with a final panorama covering the entire Côte d'Azur. The village hosts a votive festival in August with concerts, dancing and fireworks. Aspremont can be combined with Castagniers or Colomars for a circuit of the Var valley perched villages. For dining, the village has a few simple but authentic addresses serving traditional Niçois cuisine: socca, pissaladière, Swiss chard pie.",
