        routeDescription: "6 km — approximately 12 minutes via the D2204 (Paillon valley)",
        introduction: "Saint-André-de-la-Roche is a residential commune on Nice's first ring, nestled in a green valley at the entrance to the Paillon valley, just 6 km from Nice city centre. Despite its immediate proximity to the city, this commune of 5,000 inhabitants has preserved a peaceful living environment and provincial charm that make it a popular place of residence for families and workers commuting to Nice. The name 'de la Roche' evokes the rocky promontory on which the original village developed in the Middle Ages, overlooking the confluence of the Paillon de Contes and the Paillon de L'Escarène. The parish Church of Saint-André, built in the 17th century in the Niçois baroque style, is the village's main monument with its ochre facade, elegant bell tower and interior richly decorated with stucco and paintings. The old village core retains a few picturesque lanes, ancient stone houses and vestiges of medieval fortifications. The commune expanded in the second half of the 20th century with modern residential neighbourhoods stepping up the hills, enjoying a sunny aspect and valley views. Saint-André-de-la-Roche is well provided with shops, schools and local services, making it a self-sufficient commune despite its small size. The taxi journey from Nice city centre is quick and direct, following the D2204 up the Paillon valley.",
