        introduction: "Falicon is the closest perched village to Nice city centre, yet it offers a complete change of scenery. Clinging at 380 metres altitude on the flanks of Mont Chauve, this small medieval town of 2,000 inhabitants overlooks the Baie des Anges with a sweeping panorama that embraces the entire Riviera, from the Estérel to Cap Martin, with the orange checkerboard of Nice's rooftops and the deep blue of the Mediterranean in the foreground. The village is famous for the Ratapignata cave ('bats' in Niçois), a deep natural cavity beneath a dry-stone pyramid of enigmatic origin. This pyramid, which some have attributed to the Templars or ancient solar cults, has been the subject of esoteric speculation for decades and gives the place an aura of mystery. The cave itself, once accessible, is now closed for safety reasons, but the stone pyramid remains visible and the site exudes a peculiar atmosphere. The medieval village is a gem of authenticity: its cobbled lanes climb between warm-toned stone houses, pass under supporting arches and open onto shaded small squares where life flows at a Provençal pace. The parish church, dedicated to Saint-Véran, offers a fine viewpoint from its forecourt. Mont Chauve d'Aspremont (854 m), accessible by a trail from the village, is one of the most popular hiking sites for Nice residents, with a 360° panorama from its summit crowned by a former military fort. Falicon is also renowned for its olive groves and the quality of its olive oil. The journey from Nice is remarkably short — 15 minutes — but the rapid climb on the winding road gives the impression of leaving the city for another world.",
        itineraire: "From Nice, take the D2204 towards the Paillon valley, then quickly turn left onto the D114 which climbs towards Falicon. The road ascends in tight switchbacks through the residential districts of Nice's heights (Arénas, Saint-Roman-de-Bellet) before emerging onto the Falicon plateau. The village appears clinging to the mountain, its ochre stone houses standing out against the dark green of pines and olive trees. The main car park is at the village entrance, on a flat area. The entire journey is toll-free. The road is narrow in places but well surfaced and secured. The climb offers increasingly spectacular views of Nice and the sea as you gain altitude. Our drivers use this road daily and will drop you as close as possible to your destination.",
