        heroTitle: "Taxi Nice — Puget-sur-Argens",
        heroSubtitle: "At the foot of the Roquebrune Rock, between vineyards and the Argens valley",
        description: "Taxi transfer from Nice to Puget-sur-Argens, a Var commune at the foot of the spectacular Roquebrune Rock, amid Provençal vineyards and the Argens valley.",
        routeDescription: "75 km — approximately 55 minutes via the A8 motorway (exit 37)",
        introduction: "Puget-sur-Argens is an authentic Provençal commune in the Var department, nestled in the Argens plain at the foot of the spectacular Roquebrune Rock, a mass of red rhyolite rising to 373 metres that constitutes one of the most iconic landscape landmarks of the eastern Var. The commune extends across a vast fertile plain irrigated by the Argens, the longest coastal river in Provence, which crosses the territory before flowing into the Mediterranean at Fréjus. The old village, clustered around the Church of Saint-Pierre-ès-Liens and the town hall, retains a few picturesque lanes and offers a peaceful Provençal lifestyle, far from the seaside bustle of the nearby coast. Puget-sur-Argens lies at the heart of a renowned wine-growing terroir: the surrounding Côtes de Provence estates produce some of the appellation's most celebrated rosés, and several cellars welcome visitors for tastings. The commune also boasts the Base Nature François Léotard, a vast 135-hectare waterfront area (in its southern part, towards Fréjus) offering beaches, trails and free sports facilities. The proximity of the A8 motorway and the Les Arcs-Draguignan TGV station makes Puget-sur-Argens a strategic transport crossroads between Nice and the western Var. The journey from Nice is fast and direct via the A8, crossing the Esterel massif whose red porphyry cliffs plunge into the Mediterranean.",
        itineraire: "From Nice, take the A8 motorway towards Aix-en-Provence. Pass through the Nice tunnels then drive along the coast past Antibes, Cannes and Fréjus. Take exit 37 (Puget-sur-Argens / Le Muy) and follow signs to Puget-sur-Argens on the D7. The village centre is 3 km from the motorway exit. The motorway journey is smooth outside summer peak hours. Tolls amount to approximately €8 for the Nice–Le Muy section. The scenery is varied: urbanised coastline leaving Nice, then the Esterel massif with its spectacular red cliffs, and finally the Argens plain with its vineyards. The taxi drops you in the village centre or at your chosen address.",
        conseils: "The Roquebrune Rock hike (accessed from the village of Roquebrune-sur-Argens, 5 km from Puget) is unmissable: allow 2-3 hours return for a 360-degree panorama over the Maures massif, the Esterel, the Mediterranean and the Alps on clear days. The Base Nature François Léotard (accessible from Puget via the D7, 15 minutes) offers free sandy beaches, ideal for families. Wine estates around Puget produce excellent Côtes de Provence rosés: the Domaine de la Maurette and Château de Berne (20 km) are worth a detour. Puget-sur-Argens market is held on Thursday mornings in the village square. For nature lovers, the Pennafort gorges (towards Callas, 25 km) are a magnificent wild swimming spot in summer. Puget is ideally placed for visiting Fréjus (10 minutes), Saint-Raphaël (15 minutes) and the Esterel massif.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The TGV serves Les Arcs-Draguignan station (15 km from Puget) from Paris in about 4 hours. The TER from Nice to Les Arcs takes 1 hour for about €12, but the station is some distance from Puget. By private car, tolls and fuel come to about €15-20. A taxi offers a door-to-door transfer in 55 minutes from Nice, with no parking worries or connections, ideal with luggage or for families.",
