        routeDescription: "38 km — approximately 35 minutes via the A8 (Mandelieu exit) then D9",
        introduction: "Pégomas is a peaceful Provençal village nestled in the Siagne valley, between Grasse and Mandelieu-la-Napoule, which has managed to preserve its rural, authentic character despite its proximity to the Côte d'Azur. The commune is famous for its mimosa forests which, from late January to early March, transform the surrounding hills into a golden-yellow ocean of intoxicating fragrance. The Pégomas Mimosa Festival, established in 1931, is one of the oldest on the Côte d'Azur and attracts thousands of visitors each year for its flower parade, mimosa-decorated floats and the election of the Mimosa Queen. The village stretches along the Siagne, a small Provençal river with clear waters flowing down from the Caussols plateau to the Mediterranean, creating a green, fertile valley planted with olive trees, vines and orchards. The parish church of Saint-Barthélemy, the Chapel of Saint-Jean perched on a hill overlooking the village, and the old wash house bear witness to a modest but endearing rural heritage. The banks of the Siagne offer lovely shaded walks and fishing spots prized by locals. Pégomas is also a sought-after residential commune for its quality of life: countryside tranquillity just 15 minutes from Cannes and 35 minutes from Nice. The journey from Nice crosses the coastal Riviera landscape before plunging into the greenery of the Cannes hinterland.",
        itineraire: "From Nice, take the A8 motorway towards Cannes/Aix-en-Provence. After about 30 km, take exit 40 (Mandelieu-la-Napoule) and follow the D9 towards Pégomas through the Siagne valley. The road crosses wooded hills and residential areas before reaching the village centre after 8 km. The alternative via exit 42 (Mougins/Le Cannet) and the D409 is slightly longer but crosses a more rural landscape. Tolls amount to about €2 for the Nice–Mandelieu section. The taxi drops you in the village centre, at the Chapel of Saint-Jean or at your chosen address in the commune.",
        conseils: "The best time to visit Pégomas is undoubtedly mimosa season, from late January to early March. The Mimosa Festival (usually the first Sunday of February) is an unmissable event with its flower parade and Provençal entertainment. The Siagne hillsides are covered with mimosa forests that can be explored on foot (Mimosa trail, 2 hours, easy). The Chapel of Saint-Jean, a 15-minute walk from the village, offers a magnificent viewpoint over the valley. The Siagne riverbanks are perfect for a post-lunch stroll. For dining, the village has a few unpretentious but generous Provençal restaurants: try the local cuisine (daube, pieds-paquets, vegetable tian). Pégomas can be combined with Grasse (10 minutes by taxi, perfumery visits) or Mandelieu-la-Napoule (10 minutes, seaside castle) for a full day.",
        comparaisonTransport: "There is no direct public transport link between Nice and Pégomas. The journey requires a TER Nice–Cannes (30-40 min, €7) then a local bus Cannes–Pégomas (line 23, 25 min, €1.50), making at least 1h15 of travel with connections. By taxi, the 35-minute door-to-door transfer is incomparably simpler, especially with luggage or for visitors unfamiliar with the area.",
